lg.l:
With as many bodies as there are atoms in the realms. According to the Sanskrit and the
                                Chinese. The Tibetan repeats bowing with the synonym phyag tshal, presumably
                                from a text that had praṇāmaiḥ in error for pramāṇaiḥ. {2}

And words that accord with the aspirations of all beings. According to the Tibetan,
                                some Sanskrit versions and commentaries, and the Chinese. Some
                                Sanskrit versions have jina instead of jaga (“beings”). {30}

Who are turning the wheel in various ways. The Sanskrit has naya in the singular,
                                but the Tibetan has the plural tshul rnams. Yeshé Dé enumerates in his
                                commentary these various ways of guiding beings. {31}

Whose name is Samanta­bhadra. In the verse the name is given in the
                                form “Samantata­bhadra.” The Chinese has 普賢尊 (pu xian zun), “Lord
                                Samanta­bhadra.” {42}
